<!--
    Demo Task 04 - Final review for resolution (Closed / Review)
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the FOURTH of the 8-task demo dataset; together with
    tasks 01-03 and tasks 05-08, it satisfies the AAP requirement
    (Section 0.7.4) of providing demo tasks that exercise the resolve-
    blocker and resolve-success gates on both case-type flows. The
    complete 8-task fixture matrix:

        Task 01 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 02 - Closed      / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 03 - Open        / Follow-up     / parent case 04 (Pending GI)
        Task 04 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)  ## THIS FILE
        Task 05 - Closed      / Other         / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 06 - In Progress / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 07 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 08 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 09 (Resolved Complaint)

    The 8-task dataset thus exercises:
      * All 4 task types - this task is one of two demonstrators for
        the `Review` task type (the other being task 08 on case 09);
        Review represents the agent's pre-resolution validation /
        sign-off activity, where the case worker reads through the
        case body one final time, confirms all child investigations /
        follow-ups have been completed, and prepares the case for
        manager-approved resolution. Per AAP Section 0.5.7 the
        case_task type Choice list defines exactly four values -
        Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other - and Review is the
        second value, distinguishing pre-resolution sign-off from
        first-pass investigative work (Investigation), checkpoint
        questions (Follow-up), and miscellaneous administrative
        activity (Other).
      * All 3 task statuses (Open, In Progress, Closed) - this task
        contributes the SECOND of four Closed tasks (the others are
        tasks 02, 05, and 08); the Closed status is the terminal task
        status that satisfies the validate_resolved_transition
        subflow's "all child tasks must be Closed" gate, allowing the
        parent case to be transitioned from In Progress to Resolved.
      * 5 unique parent cases (03, 04, 05, 08, 09) - this task is the
        FIRST child of case 05 (the second being task 05); together,
        tasks 04 + 05 give case 05 ZERO non-Closed child tasks
        (both Closed), demonstrating that the resolve gate's
        GlideRecord query correctly returns zero rows and ALLOWS the
        In Progress -> Resolved transition. Case 05 is already in
        Resolved status in its own seed record; this task's existence
        as a Closed child of case 05 ensures the resolve gate's
        precondition was met at the time case 05 was resolved (i.e.,
        when an internal user demos by attempting to "re-resolve"
        case 05 by stepping it back through the lifecycle, the
        resolve gate will permit the transition because all child
        tasks are Closed).
      * Both flow paths (General Inquiry and Complaint) - tasks 04 + 05
        together test the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's resolve-SUCCESS path;
        tasks 01 + 02 test the GENERAL INQUIRY flow's resolve-blocker
        path; tasks 06 + 07 test the COMPLAINT flow's resolve-blocker
        path; task 08 tests the COMPLAINT flow's resolve-success path.
      * Both resolve outcomes (BLOCKED via at least one non-Closed task,
        and SUCCESS via zero non-Closed tasks) - this task is the
        FIRST enabler of the General Inquiry resolve-success path
        (paired with task 05), demonstrating that when ALL child tasks
        carry status=Closed, the validate_resolved_transition subflow
        returns zero rows and the transition is permitted.

    Lifecycle position - WHY Closed / Review / parent General Inquiry case
    Resolved is meaningful:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the resolve gate's GlideRecord query
      executed inside the validate_resolved_transition subflow is:

          var gr = new GlideRecord('x_[scope]_case_task');
          gr.addQuery('case', current.sys_id);
          gr.addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed');
          gr.query();
          if (gr.next()) {
              // BLOCK: surface the verbatim error message
              //   "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          } else {
              // ALLOW: zero non-Closed tasks - case may be Resolved
          }

      Case 05 is in Resolved status with type=General Inquiry. Both of
      its child tasks (THIS task 04 and sibling task 05) are Closed,
      so the query "case = case 05 AND status != Closed" returns ZERO
      rows. The subflow ALLOWS the In Progress -> Resolved transition.
      THIS TASK + TASK 05 ARE THE CANONICAL RESOLVE-SUCCESS PAIR FOR
      THE GENERAL INQUIRY FLOW. Where task 08 performs this enabler
      role single-handedly for case 09 on the Complaint flow, this
      task with task 05 performs the same role - in pair form - for
      case 05 on the General Inquiry flow. Note: this pairing is
      symmetric to the resolve-blocker pair (tasks 01 + 02 on case 03),
      but with all child tasks Closed instead of one Closed and one
      Open. The deliberate two-task pairing on case 05 (rather than
      a single-task demonstrator) showcases that the resolve gate's
      query operates correctly when MULTIPLE child tasks must be
      verified - the gate does not short-circuit on the first row;
      it requires ALL rows to satisfy status=Closed.

      The Review task type captures the agent's final pre-resolution
      validation work. Per the AAP's Section 0.5.7 Choice list for
      case_task type, Review is the second of four values
      (Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other), positioned after
      Investigation in the natural case-handling sequence:
      Investigation gathers facts; Review validates and synthesizes
      those facts in preparation for resolution. The "Final review
      for resolution" subject makes this lifecycle role explicit:
      the agent has investigated the case, completed any follow-up
      questions, and is now performing the FINAL pre-resolution
      check - confirming that the case body, status, and assignments
      are correct before the manager approves the Resolved -> Closed
      transition. This activity is neither an investigation
      (information-gathering) nor a follow-up (clarifying question)
      nor administrative housekeeping (Other); it is the dedicated
      pre-resolution sign-off that the Review task type is intended
      to model. The Closed status is consistent with this completed-
      review semantic: the agent reviewed the case, made any
      necessary corrections, and closed the review task before
      proceeding with resolution.

      The -1 day due_date reflects that the review task was due
      yesterday (relative to the build environment date 2026-05-01,
      i.e., 2026-04-30) and was completed on or before that date.
      This matches sibling task 05's -1 day due_date - both tasks
      were due/completed at approximately the same time, before the
      case was resolved. The relative date pattern uses negative
      offsets (1 day ago) for completed tasks, consistent with
      Closed status semantics (a task that has been started,
      performed, and closed, with a target completion date that is
      now in the past). The -1 day window is also load-bearing for
      the dashboard's "My Overdue Tasks" report contract: although
      the date qualifier (due_date < today) is satisfied, the status
      qualifier (status != Closed) excludes this task, demonstrating
      that the report correctly filters out completed-but-past-due
      tasks rather than incorrectly flagging them as overdue.

